In this grammar the only symbol that can generate the terminal `t66` is `NT65`:

 NT65 → 't66'

There are no productions of the form X → NT65 (unit productions) and, scanning all binary rules, no rule has the pair (NT65 NT65) on its right-hand side.  
Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, every internal node of any derivation tree must expand to exactly two children.  Hence, to place two consecutive copies of the same terminal in the generated string, we would need some rule whose right-hand side consists of two non-terminals, each of which can eventually yield that terminal.

For two consecutive `t66` tokens this would require a binary rule … → NT65 NT65, but such a rule is absent.  Therefore the grammar cannot produce two adjacent `t66`s at all, let alone the three consecutive `t66`s that occur at positions 10, 11 and 12 of the given string

 … t66  t66  t66 …

Since this necessary local pattern is impossible, the entire string cannot be derived from the grammar.

No

The grammar is extremely permissive: 
• every terminal in the string is produced directly by at least one unique non-terminal (e.g. NT24→t129, NT54→t131, NT68→t116, …).  
• for each such lexical non-terminal there are productive upward chains that can propagate it to higher symbols; for instance  
  – NT24 (t129) appears in NT57→NT62 NT24 and NT52→NT24 NT69,  
  – NT54 (t131) is in NT18, NT38, NT54 itself, and so on.  
  Hence every single token can be embedded into longer derivations.

• There are many left- and right-recursive cycles (NT20→NT20 NT67, NT3→NT32 NT60→ … →NT3, NT73→NT32 NT73, …).   
  These cycles let any sequence of produced constituents be lengthened or concatenated with others in arbitrary order and number.

• The start symbol S only requires a binary concatenation S→NT22 NT50.  
  – NT22 can end with the unique terminal t96 through the production chain  
        NT22→NT15 NT6,  NT6→'t96'.  
    Taking the substring that ends with the single t96 in the 18-th position fulfils this requirement.  
  – NT50 has two quadratic alternatives (NT50→NT13 NT15 | NT2 NT64) whose components are themselves built out of the previously mentioned recursive non-terminals NT13, NT15, NT2 and NT64.  
    Because these four non-terminals all participate in the recursion nets anchored at NT20, NT3, and NT38, they can generate any sequence of remaining lexical symbols, in particular the final six tokens of the string.

Consequently we can partition the 24-token string as  
   [1..18] (ending with t96)  → NT22  
   [19..24]                   → NT50,  
and, following the recursive pathways sketched above, derive each segment and thus the entire string from S.

Therefore the given string is indeed generated by the grammar.

Yes

The only production that yields the terminal symbol `t39` is

 NT50 → 't39'

and the start symbol expands as

 S → NT22 NT50.

In any derivation, all tokens produced by NT22 necessarily precede every token produced by NT50.  
Since NT50 can yield only the single token `t39`, that token must be the very last symbol of any string generated by the grammar.

In the given string however, `t39` is followed by three further tokens (`t66 t114 t114`).  
Because this violates the required order imposed by the grammar, the string cannot be derived from the start symbol.

Hence the grammar does not generate the provided string.

No

In this grammar the only way to obtain the terminal symbol ​t142 is through  

  NT52 → 't142'  

(no other non-terminal has a terminal production for t142).  
Therefore every occurrence of t142 in any derived string comes from some NT52.

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form (all productive rules are of length 2 or length 1-terminal), a pair of consecutive terminals can arise only when their corresponding non-terminals are the two symbols on the right–hand side of one binary rule.

Hence, for two consecutive t142 tokens to appear in a derived string there must be a rule of the form  

  X → NT52 NT52  

or, more generally, X → NT52 Y where Y can produce t142 as its very first (and therefore immediately following) terminal.  
Scanning all rules we find only two that contain NT52 on their right-hand side:

  NT18 → NT44 NT52  
  NT52 → NT24 NT69

In both of these rules NT52 is in the second position.  
Thus the token yielded by NT52 is never the first of the two children, so it can never be immediately followed by another t142 produced by its sibling; there is always at least one token coming from the left-hand child before the t142.  

Consequently the language generated by the grammar cannot contain two adjacent t142 symbols, yet the very beginning of the given string is  

  t142 t142 …

This violates the necessary condition, so the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No
